04720nam a22007935i 9789814951326DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898149513267 a10.1355/97898149513262doi  a(DE-B1597)582789  a(OCoLC)1243541006  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aDS597.215.A58bK46 2020 7aPOL0320002bisacsh04a959.5050922231 aKhoo, Boo Teik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Making of Anwar Ibrahim’s “Humane Economy” /cBoo Teik Khoo. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (25 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tThe Making of Anwar Ibrahim’s “Humane Economy” - EXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tThe Making of Anwar Ibrahim’s “Humane Economy”0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnwar Ibrahim, Deputy Prime Minister of Malaysia, 1993–98, and Opposition Leader, 2008–15 and since March 2020, is associated with two lasting, seemingly contradictory images. Those were of the young Anwar as a radical Islamist for whom economics seemed not to matter, and as a pro-market reformer during the 1997 East Asian financial crisis for whom Islam no longer mattered. Yet there was economics in the young Anwar’s Islam and, conversely, Islam in the mature man’s economics. Between them lay certain “moral ambivalences” that occupied Anwar during the pre-crisis period when economic growth, prosperity and ambitions were dogged by rent-seeking, corruption and institutional degradation. Anwar had expressed various thoughts on “Islam and economics”, notably when he was President of Angkatan Belia Islam Malaysia (ABIM, or Malaysian Islamic Youth Movement), Minister of Finance (1991–98), and leader of the post-Reformasi opposition. His thoughts formed the core of a “humane economy” that he envisioned and advocated upon his return to active politics from 2006 onwards. The vision of a “humane economy” holds personal, ideological and political significance at a specific political juncture in Malaysian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEconomicsxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aIslam and politicszMalaysia. 0aVice prime ministerszMalaysia. 4aPolitical Science - Essays. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Essays.2bisacsh1 aTeik, Khoo Boo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishz978311075417908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021z9783110753943oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074332640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981495132640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814951326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789814951326/original  a978-3-11-074332-6  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7  DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075417-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  aZDB-23-PLWb2021